C 25 meirt 1682
Londen M. Luey Knighley
I have heter ho hetherto exspected yd. draught on mee for the ballance due to you
wluch in case you have not don before nept post, shall oblige mee to remitt you
ats short sight, for I would by no meanes oftend you, by keeping you to long out of
yd mony, there vere pray be face there in for winsoever you Ilre pleased to serve
mee you maij alwayes espose of the valew in case I remitt nott in time to yd pleasune
I had exspected to have heand someshing more of the aurorad. butt I suppose you
found a letter coniyance for them, or not peoper for mee whoever what you please
I could wish you could finde some good pennieworth for mee in an assortiment of
or accordingly the opportunitie doth present, which in case you can send mee spedly ples
to advise to governe my self accordingly, though itt should be butt half the quantite
& some time hence the rest, in exspectation of yd answer
dhoy may serve pertely in answer to yd. of 19 san. I have don the last afford with
yd. kersies to must returne them: I exspect no more bills for acctt. of H.C. for £
hope to see that actt. cleared & frrst, for our cloth trade is to poore here & will rott
bane itt
a 25 meert 1682
London m. Heurij Sollier
In answer, to boath yd of 3 & 1w curtt., in the first send you here the invoyce of
the 2 bales of fine mathers sent to Rotterdam to m. Same bl Back to follow yd ord.
which please to peruse & finding right give yd. acct reditt, as allo for 5 ƒ flemish payd
for port of letters, & drawing out of the inelased coppy of cay. Johir a brahall his last will
bij which he makes & institutes his cousin gilbert abrahall his sole heire & epeinter for
god, itt beeng as amiple as can bemas, as to the mathers fure you must gett, there
fore do nott undervallew them, one nollet here a great dealer in that cad hash shiped
yeasterday 8 beles a board Caistian de Wever for London which he hath rec from
middelbrugh ago, & I am sure he could sell them here att ƒ40- butt upon what
autt. or hopes they go forward I know not, yett for yd spiculation
yd nesting goods I'll putt off as best i can to cleare that concernes the soondr the better, now
wee will come to the bustiynes of John vale for which I can not butt blame you the most, for
you enew before, what paines m. Soushell sook when he was here to cleare you of him
advising you never the medele with him any more, for though he is honest, would you
have us to say other wise & so to sake away a mans reputation: where any well underes
anding hath suffisient warning not to medele with such trade: & truly I did not thinck
butt you lest oft according, then you answered, butt last yeare I wrott some tinnes to RT
that I had seen of yd. goods in severatt. shops att Brussels, by which I bold him my opinion
of yd engagement againe, as now itt fals out: cloth trade can not bare itt, & T
hath by his straights brought itt so low, that wee are almost all beaten ont att Brussels
which in cases he continews, will bring hm to nothing. upon what actt. he lest off
house keeping, I know not, he is gon in with his weses mother pretending to follow
hentrad, of canelot makeing & leave the cloth trade: there by he is reputed to be so
bad a paym as ever Peeters were, & John de conincs hath had a long so many complaus
of the bills remitted on him, that I doubt not, butt he is weary on itt, & if he cheackes
him off, what shall foore John vale do, yett I hope better then you feare, & shall
waitte hun the needfull, & advise you more drept
Londen m antonij Thone son
C 25 march 1681
haveing undenstood that you are settled in londen & drive a considecable trade with
gold, desire to be informed how that com. now oules wish you, & what spiculation you have
of the future to gov. my self accordingly, for I have some farcells, & if the prises do
incorridge shall send some for a brgatl, whilst in exspectation of yd answer
C 25d.
London m. witf. Pindan
In answer to yd of the 2t curtt. as to the debt of seaman is realy & can be susttienthey
proved, butt should the sharges be so greatt, itt would be better to endeavour with him
by fare meanes, on threaightning of arresting, & itt may be, he will finde out away to
procure pay for you, which if he doh not advise mee, I have understood of some
of his goods, or bagage that is some where here to be kept for his ord, I'll endeavour
to arrest that, in the meane while do yd endeavour with you, to finde him out
& to neeave from hun what you can gett, Philip vander sught hath sence payd
seonely seamans bustijnes keeps our liqidation standing yett I hope you shall not losse
London mr. Juny Maynand
mij last to you was on the 21 curtt. sence yett non from you, which gives mee opinion
that severall posts are wantingh with you, yett I hope you are m a good forwardnest
of the disineed goods, add to the inordered fan Cos cloathes one gray more of the key
as N. 957, of which inclosed a pat. as alse 2 a 3 drap cullours 7 ƒ cloathes or kers. of
937„ 939 & 940, 939 beeng the best cullour of which here under a pat the wallones are
still & vere much for drap cullours off a lovely blewish mixture much like the patt. here
inder, though lighten, so do yd endeavour as well you can, to send good goods & good cullours
& mixture. a handsome list is a good qualitie in the sale of a cloth for yd gon &
inclosed a patt. of stamet made abont lille, & vere much demanded here, butt not vere
